## **Overview**

This chatbot utilizes an open source Rasa framework, trained with a Huggingface mode (BERT).  
Fallback responses are handled by OpenAI’s GPT4 via api requests. The model can be interacted with through a chat widget running on a flask server. This is hosted on a custom AWS instance

Design Diagram

## Data Collection

Using the requests library in Python, data from each FAQ article was able to be collected.   
Due to the website's structure, a simple iteration through each category, followed by an iteration through each article in the category is sufficient to encapsulate all of the FAQ. ![][image1]  
With some cleaning, each article is able to be segmented into rules and responses based on the text within headers and headings or paragraphs respectively. 

![][image2]  
This data will be refined further once we have decided on the framework to use for our model. 

## Model Choices

There are several chat frameworks to consider for this project, each with their own pros and cons. For the sake of this project we are going to assume this chatbot would be deployed to a large user base and incur high volumes of usage.

**GPT4**: High natural language understanding, needs little training/setup to be functional out of the box. Usage-based pricing can become expensive with high-traffic. Higher latency. Cloud-based which can introduce privacy or uptime concerns.

**Rasa:** Highly customizable, with no licensing costs. Full data ownership, can run locally providing more control and privacy. No pretrained models, struggles with ambiguous inputs without high levels of training. Requires more development effort to set up and train.

**Dialogflow:** Great natural language understanding. Includes FAQ templates for chatbots. Built in integrations for Slack, Google Assistant, etc. Tied to Google Cloud, requires storing data on Google Servers.

**Microsoft Bot Framework:** Enterprise ready. Integrations with Azure, Teams, etc. Strong analytic tools. Steeper learning curve for setup. Can incur high costs for large-scale usage. Less dynamic for unstructured conversation. 

**Winner: Rasa**  
While this assignment’s scope is narrow, I believe **Rasa** provides the most benefits to being used in a high-volume environment. The fact that it is open source and can run locally gives more control over data privacy and reduces costs immensely. 

**Honorable mention: GPT4**  
GPT4 offers a very robust api for conducting a natural conversation. We will combine this model with Rasa and utilize it in fallback scenarios. This will make the bot feel much more versatile, while putting most of the weight on Rasa. 

## **Data Preprocessing**

Rasa trains using 3 different yaml files: nlu.yml, domain.yml and rules.yml. 

We will use Python to separate our scraped data into these formats. This will require extracting intents, examples, and responses. Since we want our model to understand a variety of question formats for one response, we will need to expand our dataset further. 

#### GPT Expansion

“Generate.py” feeds each row of our dataframe into the ChatGPT4 api and allows the LLM to expand our data. It is tasked with splitting collected data into intents and populating with 4-5 examples each. Additionally, it will output this data into domain.yml and nlu.yml.

Example input

Topic: “Pinning”,   
Data: “Imagine being a wizard in your own app kingdom, conjuring your most beloved content to the forefront of your realm. That’s what our Pinning feature is all about\! Whether it's showcasing your persona in your Profile or keeping crucial convos at your fingertips in the Inbox, Pinning lets you highlight what matters most”

Example output

nlu:  
  \- intent: pin\_feature\_overview  
    examples: |  
      \- What is pinning?  
      \- Can you tell me about the pin feature?  
      \- How does the pinning function work?  
      \- I need an overview of pinning.  
      \- Explain the pinning feature.

responses:  
  utter\_pin\_feature\_overview:  
    \- text: "Pinning allows you to highlight important content in your profile or feed. Imagine conjuring your beloved content to the forefront of your app. Our Pinning feature allows you to highlight what matters most, be it your Profile or crucial conversations in the Inbox."

#### Rules.yml

Finally, we need to generate our rules.yml file. This is responsible for mapping intents to responses as well as handling any code execution we might want our model to perform. 

Due to our naming convention, this can be done with basic text manipulation. “ymlCombine.py” takes each intent and adds the prefix “utter” to find its matching response. It then formats the match into our rules.yml file. 

  \- rule: Respond to pin\_feature\_overview  
    steps:  
      \- intent: pin\_feature\_overview  
      \- action: utter\_pin\_feature\_overview

## Actions

At some points we want our model to execute code blocks. This will be utilized for Logging, Feedback handling, and our fallback to GPT4’s api. This can be found in ./actions/actions.py. These actions are accessible through a separate actions server hosted on port 5055 by Rasa.

### Logging

After every intent is registered, an entry is made within the log file. This will help find under what conditions our fallback is triggered as well as giving us a growing dataset we can eventually fine tune our model with

Example General Log:   
2024-11-24 18:53:30,925 \- User: Explain profile 4.0, Intent: profile\_changes\_overview, Bot Response: Profile 4.0 is a complete overhaul of our user profile design. It showcases animated avatars and allows for a continuous, scrollable profile interface, making it more engaging and user-friendly.

### Feedback

After a non-conversational response is provided, the model will prompt the user to provide feedback through two buttons: helpful and unhelpful. 

![][image3]

Depending on the user's choice, this chat instance will be logged within helpful.log or unhelpful.log. 

## Training 

The training pipeline for our Rasa bot is simple due to the scope of the project.  
It consists of 4 steps: 

**WhitespaceTokenizer**:  
Splits the input text into individual words or tokens using spaces as separators.  
Example: "I love coding" → \["I", "love", "coding"\]

**LexicalSyntacticFeaturizer:**  
Creates basic features for the tokens, such as word shapes, prefixes, suffixes, and part-of-speech tags.These features help the model understand the structure of the text.

**LanguageModelFeaturizer**:  
Uses a HuggingFace language model (BERT) to generate high-quality embeddings for each token. This helps establish meaning and context of the words in a sentence. 

**DIETClassifier:**  
A neural network that predicts intents and extracts entities from the processed text.  
(Trained with just 100 epochs)

After running “Rasa train”, our model is ready\! We can access it by using “Rasa run” and interact with it via SocketIO on port 5005\.

### **Future Improvements** 

With a limited time to complete this project, there are many improvements I would still like to make that will greatly improve the models effectiveness. 

**Entity Mapping:**   
Our intents can be divided into entities to help the model differentiate between similarly structured requests. “entities.py” uses ChatGPT4 api to generate this data for us but I lack the compute power to train the model on this new data within a reasonable amount of time.  

Example data with marked entities:  

  \- intent: how\_to\_pin  
    examples: |  
      \- How do I \[pinning\](action) a \[post\](object)?  
      \- Can you guide me on \[pinning\](action) a \[creation\](object)?  
      \- What steps do I follow to \[pinning\](action) an \[item\](object)?  
      \- Tell me how to \[pinning\](action) something.  
      \- How can I \[pinning\](action) \[content\](object) in my \[feed\](object)?

**Synonyms:**   
Creating a synonym list works in tandem with custom entities. Similar words can be linked to provide better intent prediction. I implemented a simple synonyms table as an example:   
synonyms:  
  pinning:  
    \- pin  
    \- highlight

While “pinning” is the only real entity, our model will understand that “pin” and “highlight” refer to the same thing.

**Better data refinement:**   
Some examples in the nlu.yml and domain.yml contain overlapping information and similar contexts that can either be combined or reworded for clarity. This would benefit from a by-hand passover and would improve the models intent prediction (reducing false positives)

**Learning from Logs**  
The logs generated from the model can be used to train the model to make fewer mistakes. A pipeline can be set up to retrain the model using its common mistakes. Identify misclassified intents, incorrectly extracted entities, and unexpected bot responses by comparing:

* The predicted intent vs. the correct intent.  
* The extracted entities vs. the expected entities.

Improvements can also be made from identifying cases where a user rephrased their question multiple times. 

## **Running the model**

1. Clone the repository : [zacharyrussell/HighriseChatbot](https://github.com/zacharyrussell/HighriseChatbot)  
2. Create a .env file with your OpenAI api token  
3. Run pip install \-r requirements.txt to install dependencies  
4. Verify Rasa is installed properly “Rasa –version:   
   1. You may need to run pip install Rasa separately  
      1. If this fails, run pip install cryptography==41.0.7  
      2. You may need to switch your environment to Python 3.9  
   2. You may need to run pip install transformers  
   3. You may need to run pip install openai  
5. In 3 separate terminals run these commands  
   1. rasa run actions (Set up the actions endpoint)  
   2. rasa run \--enable-api \--cors "\*"  
   3. Navigate to ./Server  
      1. Python3 server.py  
6. A webpage will be available on your localhost port 8000
